"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513552","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Department has not made an estimate.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-21T15:15:40.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513552/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513552/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-18","Income Support","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's latest estimate is of the number of parents with children who will be claiming income support in April 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","34289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513553","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-21","<p>We do not issue forecasts of these volumes. Forecasts of volumes will be published once the data series is established and robust.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-04-21T15:07:58.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513553/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513553/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-18","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's latest estimate is of the number of parents with children who will be claiming universal credit in April 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","34290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513554","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-26","<p>The report of the Industrial Injuries Advisory Council (May 2014) included recommended criteria for including Dupuytren’s Contracture in the list of prescribed diseases. The Government is continuing to consider the recommended criteria and any other relevant factors.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-26T14:37:12.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513554/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513554/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-18","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit: Dupuytren's Contracture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria his Department is using to determine whether Dupuytren's Contracture should be included on the list of prescribed diseases covered by Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","34284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513555","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-04-26","<p>The government does not record information on the average time taken to consider recommendations from the Industrial Injuries Advisory Council.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-04-26T14:40:51.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513555/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513555/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-04-18","Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what average time has been taken for the Governemnt to determine whether an illness or disease should be included on the list of prescribed diseases covered by Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit following a recommendation by the Industrial Injuries Advisory Council.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","34285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513556","Attorney General","false","2016-04-26","<p>Mandatory training relating to disability hate crime was delivered, across the Crown Prosecution Service, between September 2015 and January 2016.</p><p>Prosecutors will deploy the knowledge gained from the training in the course of prosecutions thereby improving performance.</p><p>The CPS are enhancing the support provided to prosecutors in dealing with crimes committed against disabled people. They are reviewing their policy and legal guidance on disability hate crime, which will provide assurance to the public of how the CPS intends to deal with such crimes.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-26T10:08:21.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513556/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513556/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-18","Hate Crime: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what progress his Department has made on providing disability hate crime training for all prosecutors; and what improvements this training will bring to conviction rates.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","34335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513557","Attorney General","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Serious Fraud Office has received self-reports from companies but it would not be appropriate to confirm numbers.</p><p> </p><p>The process of reaching Deferred Prosecution Agreements (DPAs) happens in stages. Initial negotiations are confidential to encourage openness on the part of the company. Under the Criminal Procedure Rules, the Court determines whether any relevant hearings are heard in public or in private. Any DPA must be approved by a judge and publicised.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-21T11:10:30.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513557/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513557/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-18","Companies: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many companies have self-reported to the Serious Fraud Office for a Deferred Prosecution Agreement.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","34312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513558","Attorney General","false","2016-04-21","<p>Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunal Service (HMCTS) have responsibility for the enforcement of all domestic confiscation orders. The CPS assists in the enforcement process when it can add value, such as by managing restraint orders, seeking the appointment of enforcement receivers or by requesting mutual legal assistance from overseas jurisdictions in respect of assets located abroad. When the CPS can no longer provide additional value, the lead enforcement role reverts to the HMCTS and the CPS no longer monitors its progress.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The latest CPS data relates to February 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Over the last twelve months outstanding debt (excluding interest) has decreased by 18.4% from £505,598,593 to £412,652,493.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CPS is leading in the enforcement of 1172 confiscation orders and the outstanding debt, excluding interest is £412,652,493 of which £157,210,118 or 38.1% has been assessed as being realistically recoverable.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Court determines the recoverable amount and an assessment of what is recoverable is carried out by the CPS on a monthly basis in respect of all cases. The majority of unrecoverable assets are hidden, whilst the remainders consist of assets where there are third party claims; the assets are held in jurisdictions where the authorities have taken the view that the defendant does not have the interest in the asset; or where the asset has simply diminished in value.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-21T17:12:15.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513558/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513558/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-18","Confiscation Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how much debt remains outstanding under confiscation orders obtained by the CPS; and what recent estimate he has made of how much of that debt is recoverable.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","34436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513559","Attorney General","false","2016-04-21","The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) does not maintain any centrally held data that would enable the identification of the nationality of any defendants, whether they are an EU national or not. Such information could only be obtained through a manual search of records which would incur disproportionate cost.","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2016-04-21T11:00:53.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513559/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513559/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-04-18","Homicide and Sexual Offences: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what proportion of (a) murder, (b) rape and (c) sexual assault cases were prosecuted where the defendant was a non-EU national in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","34464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513560","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-25","<p>International maritime law recognises that the legislation of the flag state is normally applied onboard a vessel and therefore the UK Government is unable to insist its legislation (including employment legislation) is applied on non-UK registered vessels.</p><p> </p><p>However rules on redundancy are quite clearly defined in UK legislation and a UK seafarer, working on a UK registered vessel, would be protected by the legislation even where the vessel operates in international waters. If it is believed that this legislation has been circumvented then there is potentially grounds for unfair dismissal and, if necessary, this can be pursued through an employment tribunal.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-04-25T10:54:05.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513560/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513560/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-18","Offshore Industry: Redundancies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to prevent redundancies of British crews and their replacement with cheaper foreign crews in the offshore supply sector.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","34463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513561","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-25","<p>Broadband Delivery UK are working closely with BT and other suppliers to deliver our Manifesto commitment to provide 95% of the UK with access to superfast broadband by the end of 2017. Almost 4 million homes and business now have access to superfast broadband for the first time thanks to the Superfast Broadband Programme. In addition, BT has recently announced an additional £179m of supplier funding for the programme under the contractual profit sharing arrangements. BDUK also has rigorous controls in place to ensure that all investment is in areas that will not be reached commercially for at least three years, and represents value for money.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-25T08:48:00.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513561/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513561/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-18","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that BT co-operates with Broadband Delivery UK in rolling out superfast broadband in areas not covered by the commercial rollout.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","34428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513562","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-05-09","<p>This matter was addressed in the Oral Statement given by my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills on 11 April 2016 (Hansard Vol 608, Cols 50 and 51). The Department was informed in confidence by Tata in mid-February that the company was seriously considering the closure of the Port Talbot plant. The Government was not prepared to let that happen, and together with others in Government my Rt Hon Friend worked with Tata to persuade the company to instead keep the plant open, run a sale process (which was launched by Tata on 11 April 2016), and find a new buyer.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-05-09T14:06:47.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513562/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513562/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Tata Steel: Port Talbot","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on what dates Tata Steel first informed him that it (a) was considering selling the Port Talbot plant and (b) had decided to do so.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513563","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-28","<p>Tata Group plc is a Strategic Relationship-Managed company and my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) is the Contact Minister. He has had regular meetings with the company, including during the Prime Minister of India’s visit to the UK in November 2015. BIS Ministers have held discussions and corresponded with Tata Group plc on a regular basis on issues of importance to the company’s investments in the UK. Most recently my right hon. Friend visited Mumbai on 6 April and again on 20 April to progress the sale of Tata Steel’s UK assets with Cyrus Mistry, Tata Group Chairman.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","34333","2016-04-28T10:41:21.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513563/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513563/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Tata Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on how many and which occasions he has had communications with Tata Group plc in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513564","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p>There has not yet been an assessment of the potential location for the new Institute for Apprenticeships.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-21T15:56:09.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513564/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513564/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Institute for Apprenticeships: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment his Department has made of the suitability of Sheffield as a potential location for the new Institute for Apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513565","Department for Education","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Equality Act 2010 already protects employees from direct disability discrimination where they are diagnosed with cancer, HIV and multiple sclerosis, any of which may be terminal illnesses. Where a diagnosis of serious illness is not (or not initially) terminal, protection from discrimination would still be available where an employee’s condition fits the definition of a disability, which in the 2010 Act is defined as a physical or mental impairment that has a substantial and long-term adverse effect on their ability to carry out normal day-to-day activities.</p><p>Where a disabled employee is dismissed because they have a terminal illness, they can seek redress under the 2010 Act. Also, should an employer effectively force such an employee to resign from their job, the constructive dismissal provisions in employment law may be applicable.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-04-26T16:16:41.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513565/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513565/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will make it her policy to bring forward legislative proposals to make terminal illness a protected characteristic in order to ensure that employees cannot be dismissed for being terminally ill.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","34383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513566","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-28","<p>Tata Group plc is a Strategic Relationship-Managed company and my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) is the Contact Minister. He has had regular meetings with the company, including during the Prime Minister of India’s visit to the UK in November 2015. BIS Ministers have held discussions and corresponded with Tata Group plc on a regular basis on issues of importance to the company’s investments in the UK. Most recently my right hon. Friend visited Mumbai on 6 April and again on 20 April to progress the sale of Tata Steel’s UK assets with Cyrus Mistry, Tata Group Chairman.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","34377","2016-04-28T10:41:20.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513566/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513566/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Tata Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, on which occasions he had communications with Tata Group plc in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513568","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>Attendance at Committee meetings is a matter of public record. Transcripts of such appearances can be found in Hansard and on the Business, Innovation and Skills Select Committee web page here: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/business-innovation-and-skills/inquiries/" target="_blank">www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/business-innovation-and-skills/inquiries/</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-25T13:30:20.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513568/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513568/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Business, Innovation and Skills Select Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many times he has attended public meetings of the Business, Innovation and Skills Committee since his appointment.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","34347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513569","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Cyber Innovation Centre in Cheltenham will help local innovators develop new cyber security products and start new companies. This will have a direct benefit to the tech sector in Cheltenham, a benefit which will increase over time as these start-ups grow into what we hope will be world-class firms.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-22T13:48:58.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513569/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513569/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-18","Cyber Innovation Centre: Cheltenham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of the likely benefits the Cyber Innovation Centre will bring to Cheltenham's local economy.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","34343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513570","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Higher Education is a devolved matter. In England the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) has statutory responsibility for assessing quality in the provision that it funds. There are parallel quality assessment (QA) arrangements in place that apply to alternative providers.</p><p> </p><p>Officials in my Department have held a number of discussions with the devolved administrations and with HEFCE regarding HEFCE’s recent Review of Quality Assessment and its outcomes, including on how we are maintaining a cohesive, UK-wide approach to quality assessment. Further information on our future approach to quality assessment, across all types of HE providers, will be announced when we publish the response to our Higher Education Green Paper.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34507 ; 34508","2016-04-21T16:10:35.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513570/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513570/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Higher Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of proposals arising from the Review of Quality Assessment on the (a) cohesiveness of the UK-wide system of quality assessment and (b) adoption of that system by other countries.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","34506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513571","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Higher Education is a devolved matter. In England the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) has statutory responsibility for assessing quality in the provision that it funds. There are parallel quality assessment (QA) arrangements in place that apply to alternative providers.</p><p> </p><p>Officials in my Department have held a number of discussions with the devolved administrations and with HEFCE regarding HEFCE’s recent Review of Quality Assessment and its outcomes, including on how we are maintaining a cohesive, UK-wide approach to quality assessment. Further information on our future approach to quality assessment, across all types of HE providers, will be announced when we publish the response to our Higher Education Green Paper.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34506 ; 34508","2016-04-21T16:10:35.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513571/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513571/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Higher Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether the funding councils' proposals arising from the Review of Quality Assessment will subject all UK universities, further education colleges offering UK higher education provision and all alternative providers, including their international reach, to the same system of external quality review.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","34507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513572","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-21","<p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Higher Education is a devolved matter. In England the Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) has statutory responsibility for assessing quality in the provision that it funds. There are parallel quality assessment (QA) arrangements in place that apply to alternative providers.</p><p> </p><p>Officials in my Department have held a number of discussions with the devolved administrations and with HEFCE regarding HEFCE’s recent Review of Quality Assessment and its outcomes, including on how we are maintaining a cohesive, UK-wide approach to quality assessment. Further information on our future approach to quality assessment, across all types of HE providers, will be announced when we publish the response to our Higher Education Green Paper.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","34506 ; 34507","2016-04-21T16:10:35.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513572/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513572/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Higher Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions his Department has had with the devolved administrations on the implications for their policies of the outcome of the Review of Quality Assessment.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","34508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513573","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government published its Impact Assessment of the National Living Wage on 7 December 2015.</p><p>2.9 million workers are expected to directly benefit from the National Living Wage by 2020, 8% of which are located in the South East of England. The Department has made no detailed assessment of the benefits of the National Living Wage at local authority level.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-04-28T15:47:51.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513573/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513573/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Living Wage: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of the workforce in Southampton is in receipt of the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","34512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513574","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>Following the review by HM Treasury in 2012 of the tax arrangements of senior public sector appointees, departments are responsible for publishing information on temporary appointments and other contingent labour in their annual accounts.</p><p> </p><p>Before 2012, such transparency did not exist.</p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-21T09:17:53.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513574/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513574/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-18","Civil Servants: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the policy of publishing details of officials who earn more than the Prime Minister applies to temporary appointments.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513575","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Government intends to produce a report in due course that will set out how the UK is contributing to the Global Goals.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2016-04-26T09:32:35.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513575/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513575/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-18","Government Departments: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 15 April 2016 to Question 32701, if his Department will publish findings of its review into the consistency of Government plans and policies with the Global Goals.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","34357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513576","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Cabinet Office has previously supported Sheffield and Cardiff Universities in piloting such initatives. The Government is also working with student organistions such as Universities UK, and Association of Colleges to support the drive to ensure as many eligible people as possible are registered to vote.</p><p>Though for the most part, academic enrolment will not commence until September Higher education institutions, including Universities, are free to choose to integrate registration with their student enrolment processes. We strongly encourage them to do so.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-04-26T12:47:09.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513576/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513576/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-18","Electoral Register: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department plans to work with universities, colleges and further education providers to integrate electoral registration into academic enrolment before (a) the May 2016 elections and EU referendum and (b) the 2016-17 academic year.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","34387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513577","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-22","<p>Details of the Anti-Corruption Champion's travel and related costs will be published on an annual basis on GOV.UK in due course.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-22T09:28:19.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513577/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513577/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-18","Cabinet Office: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which countries the Government Anti-Corruption Champion has visited in the course of his official duties.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513578","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>This is a matter for individual departments who are responsible for determining the level of information required for their online forms.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-21T10:34:27.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513578/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513578/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-18","Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if his Department will take steps to allow web-users to include honours when completing government online forms.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","34465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513579","Cabinet Office","false","2016-05-04","<p>As I made clear in the House on 27 April, we are continuing to consider the comments of all interested parties, ahead of the introduction into grant agreements of the clause aimed at protecting taxpayers' money from being wasted on government lobbying government. We are pausing the implementation, pending a review of the representations made, and to give further time to consider any necessary adjustments to the wording of the clause, or the policy on its implementation, to help to deliver this policy in the best possible way for all involved.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-05-04T09:44:38.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513579/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513579/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-18","Science: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of representations from the science community to his Department's plans to insert a new clause into all new and renewed grant agreements.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","34452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513580","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) occupies Abbey House, Telford, under the terms of its STEPS PFI contract which runs to 2 April 2021. The Department has a rolling agreement with Land Registry to use part of their space at Parkside Court.</p><p> </p><p>In November 2015, HMRC announced its plans to create a Regional Centre in Birmingham and a Specialist Site in Telford as part of its UK wide Building our Future Locations Programme. HMRC will use flexibility provisions within its occupancy agreements at both Abbey House and Parkside Court to align their closure with the opening of its new facilities. Specialist roles will remain in Telford with others moving to the new Regional Centre.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-25T13:34:05.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513580/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513580/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Revenue and Customs: Telford","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 18 March 2016 to Question 30728, what plans HM Revenue and Customs has for the future of its staff currently working in Abbey House and Parkside Court after the expiration of the leases of those buildings.","false","Biography information for Lucy Allan","Telford","Lucy Allan","34462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513581","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-26","<p>HMRC has a Whistleblowing and Raising a Concern Policy. Since April 2014 concerns raised under this policy have been captured centrally but the data has been captured at a high level and does not have sufficient detail to enable HMRC to reliably identify concerns relating to customers of the High Net Worth Unit and Large Business Unit over the last 5 years.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not offer preferential treatment to any tax payer or group. HMRC is even handed in its treatment of all customers, and manages different customers by allocating its resources to those groups which need more support or present higher risks of not meeting their tax obligations.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-26T13:30:15.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513581/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513581/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Revenue and Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on how many occasions in the last five years HM Revenue and Customs officials have raised concerns internally that UK taxpayers who are customers of the (a) High Net Worth Unit and (b) Large Business Unit have received preferential or inappropriate tax treatment as a result of their position.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","34460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513582","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-22","<p>These are matters for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and relate to FCA Guidance Consultation (GC16/2) issued on the interpretation of provisions in the Consumer Credit Act 1974, regarding whether a default notice should be given to a guarantor before payment is taken from them when a borrower defaults. The FCA is currently considering responses to the consultation and will publish a response after considering the complex issues raised.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","34271 ; 34272","2016-04-22T10:24:17.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513582/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513582/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Loans: Defaulters","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information his Department holds on the reasons for the FCA changing its policy on whether guarantor lenders should have to issue legal default notices on borrowers before collecting money from guarantors as set in PS15/23, of September 2015, to that set in GC16/2, of February 2016.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","34433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513583","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Government will conduct further sales of RBS shares subject to market conditions, and in doing so will maximise value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The OBR presented an estimate of future proceeds in the March 2016 Budget.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-22T10:20:07.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513583/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513583/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the potential price per share at sale of the Government's 73 per cent stake in the Royal Bank of Scotland compared to the amount paid per share in 2008.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","34434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513585","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-26","<p>The British people are asking for the facts before they decide whether to vote Remain or Leave in the EU referendum. The Treasury’s analysis shows that if the UK leaves the EU, the UK would be permanently poorer and it estimates an annual loss of 6.2% of GDP after 15 years, which is equivalent to £4,300 per UK household.</p><p>The Treasury is appropriately resourced to support the Government’s priorities in Europe. However, it is not practical to identify full-time equivalent staff numbers.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-26T16:07:59.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513585/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513585/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) cost of labour and (b) other expenses incurred by his Department was in producing its analysis of costs if the UK were to leave the EU; and how many man hours were required to produce that analysis.","false","Biography information for Michael Fabricant","Lichfield","Michael Fabricant","34408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513586","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>Data for full-time equivalent Civil servants working in HM Treasury are published on .gov.uk and can be found using the link below.</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmt-workforce-management-information-december-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hmt-workforce-management-information-december-2015</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are unable to supply information on employees who may work on the Northern Powerhouse agenda as our system does not give a breakdown of staff to that level. Therefore to supply this information would be at a disproportionate cost.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-25T13:17:28.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513586/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513586/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Treasury: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) full-time equivalent civil servants work in his Department and (b) civil servants work full-time on the Northern Powerhouse agenda.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513587","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Chancellor has set out the government’s view on the challenges facing the UK economy at budget on 16 March 2016. The transcript of the speech is available from:</p><p>www.gov.uk/government/speeches/budget-2016-george-osbornes-speech</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Bank of England’s December 2015 Financial Stability Report sets out analysis on the exposures of UK banks to commodity sectors. The full report can be found here:</p><p>www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Pages/fsr/2015/dec.aspx</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-22T10:22:59.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513587/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513587/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Offshore Industry: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the rising default rate of companies in the oil and gas sector on their high-yield loans on wider stability of the financial sector.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","34368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513588","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Government has fundamentally reformed regulation of the consumer credit market, transferring regulatory responsibility from the Office of Fair Trading (OFT) to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) on 1 April 2014. This more robust regulatory system is helping to deliver the Government’s vision for a well-functioning and sustainable consumer credit market which is able to meet consumers’ needs.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA has incorporated key elements of OFT guidance on continuous payment authorities (CPAs) into its rules. In particular, firms are required not to use CPA if there is reason to believe that there are insufficient funds in the borrower’s account, or that this will leave insufficient funds for priority debts or other essential living expenses. Lenders must also show forbearance if there is evidence of financial difficulty.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA have introduced rules to limit payday lenders’ use of CPAs to two unsuccessful attempts to withdraw funds from the customer’s account. The FCA has also banned CPA part payment, so that a lender can only take payment if the whole owed sum is available in the customer’s account. The FCA can use its flexible rule-making powers to take further action where it deems necessary to protect consumers.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-25T13:21:08.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513588/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513588/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Credit: Interest Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward proposals for tighter regulation of companies that carry out payment processing on behalf of payday loan companies.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","34402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513589","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>Once formally notified of the proposed merger, the Bank of England and the Financial Conduct Authority (as supervisors of the London Stock Exchange Group’s UK-authorised subsidiaries) must assess the proposal from a regulatory standpoint.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the proposed merger must be approved by competition authorities and is subject to a range of other assessments including those of overseas regulators and shareholders.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","34500","2016-04-25T13:18:44.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513589/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513589/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the anti-trust implications of the proposed merger between the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","34499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513590","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>Once formally notified of the proposed merger, the Bank of England and the Financial Conduct Authority (as supervisors of the London Stock Exchange Group’s UK-authorised subsidiaries) must assess the proposal from a regulatory standpoint.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the proposed merger must be approved by competition authorities and is subject to a range of other assessments including those of overseas regulators and shareholders.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","34499","2016-04-25T13:18:44.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513590/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513590/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for economic security of the proposed merger between the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","34500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513591","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs officials meet with and receive representations from a wide variety of organisations as part of the policy formulation and delivery process. As has been the practice of successive administrations, it is not the Government’s practice to give details of any such discussion.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-26T16:09:13.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513591/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513591/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Revenue and Customs: Bircham Dyson Bell","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, on how many occasions between 2006 and 2011 HM Revenue and Customs officials (a) met and (b) communicated with Peter Twiddy, a consultant who worked at Bircham Dyson Bell.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","34491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513592","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>HM Revenue and Customs does not divulge details about an individual’s tax affairs.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-25T13:32:08.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513592/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513592/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Tony Blair","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what information he holds on what discussions have taken place between HM Revenue and Customs and former Prime Minister Mr Tony Blair or his advisers about (a) Mr Blair's tax affairs and (b) charges brought in under the Finance Act 2006 as they relate to those tax affairs.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","34492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513593","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Government’s shareholding in RBS is managed at arm’s length from HM Treasury by UK Financial Investments (UKFI). However, UKFI’s role is to manage the investment, not the bank. RBS retains its own independent Board of Directors. Commercial decisions such as lending remain the responsibility of the bank’s independent management team and not the Government.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-22T10:21:30.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513593/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513593/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Royal Bank of Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made on the potential selling price of the Government's remaining stake in the Royal Bank of Scotland of the implications for the leveraged loans made by that bank to the oil and gas sector of the default rate of companies in that sector on high-yield loans.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","34493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513594","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-25","<p>The £500 million Access Fund is part of the Department for Transport's overall contribution to the Local Growth Fund in this spending review period. As with the majority of the Local Growth Fund it is available to Local Enterprise Partnerships to bid for and spend in line with their own priorities. LEPs are already planning to spend considerably more than £500 million on sustainable transport and we would encourage them to propose ambitious sustainable transport measures in their further growth deal bids this year.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-04-25T14:20:32.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513594/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513594/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-18","Transport: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that the £500 million Access Fund is spent on sustainable transport projects.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","34444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513595","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Local Growth Fund is competitively awarded to Local Enterprise Partnerships based on the strength of their plans for driving economic growth in their areas. The Secretary of State has written to all LEPs setting out the basis on which further awards will be made later this year. The government is encouraging bold and ambitious bids for this further funding, which will be assessed competitively based on the quality of the proposals submitted.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-04-25T14:14:29.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513595/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513595/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-18","Local Growth Deals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how funding is allocated for the Local Growth Fund; and if he will publish formal guidance on the bidding process for local enterprise partnerships.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","34445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513596","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-21","<p>The higher rates of Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT) for additional properties was introduced to try to make it fairer for people trying to get their foot on the property ladder. Under SDLT legislation, there are exemptions to the tax, including the higher rates, for certain acquisitions by registered social landlords.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-21T14:19:50.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513596/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513596/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-18","Social Rented Housing: Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Higher Stamp Duty Land Tax rates announced in Budget 2016 will be levied on properties acquired by social landlords under Section 106 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","34489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513597","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Department has made no estimate of the number of local authority areas in which the Safe Places scheme is used.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-21T13:22:20.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513597/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513597/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-18","Vulnerable Adults: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the number of local authority areas in which the Safe Places scheme is used.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","34488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513598","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-26","<p>There was an estimated 23.4 million dwellings in England as of 31 March 2014, an increase of 137,000 dwellings on the previous year. This includes 4 million social and affordable rented dwellings (Private Registered Providers plus local authority tenures) (1).</p><p>We are doubling the housing budget to deliver one million more homes, including spending £8 billion to build 400,000 new affordable housing starts by 2021, the biggest new affordable homes programme since the 1970s, and committing £2.3 billion towards delivering 200,000 new Starter Homes.</p><p>(1) Source: DCLG Dwelling Stock Estimate, 2014, England <br>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/423249/Dwelling_Stock_Estimates_2014_England.pdf</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-04-26T13:10:14.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513598/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513598/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-18","Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment the Government has made of the current level of housing provisions; and what steps he is taking to ensure that the most vulnerable have access to suitable housing.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","34336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513599","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-21","<p>There are currently 1651 full time equivalent civil servants working in the Department for Communities and Local Government.</p><p>The Northern Powerhouse is a key ambition of this Government which requires input from officials across DCLG and other Government Departments, across a wide range of policy areas. This enables bottom-up ownership of the Northern Powerhouse agenda by Northern areas to ensure the North can influence, direct and benefit from the Northern Powerhouse, including through Devolution Deals.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-04-21T13:18:17.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513599/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513599/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-18","Department for Communities and Local Government: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many (a) full-time equivalent civil servants work in his Department and (b) civil servants work full-time on the Northern Powerhouse agenda.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513600","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-27","<p>No timetable has been set for when Section 154 of the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 will be commenced.</p><p> </p><p>Defra has announced plans for a new litter strategy and we are working with industry, experts and councils across England to improve the way we all tackle the scourge of litter. The litter strategy will promote affordable and replicable ways to influence littering behaviour and reduce littering. This will include work on ways to deal with littering from vehicles.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-04-27T12:15:24.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513600/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513600/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Litter: Fixed Penalties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to commence Section 154 of the Anti-Social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014, on fixed penalty notices for leaving litter.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","34309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513601","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Government will set out its plans for the future of the BBC in a White Paper in the Spring.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-21T11:36:43.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513601/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513601/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-18","BBC Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what his plans are for the body that will replace the BBC Trust.","false","Biography information for Nic Dakin","Scunthorpe","Nic Dakin","34394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513602","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-25","<p>Internet Service Providers are accountable to Ofcom - and in turn to their customers - through Ofcom's 'General Conditions (14)'. These conditions include ensuring that an effective complaint handling procedure is in place, and Ofcom can impose a penalty of up to 10% of turnover for failure to comply.</p><p>Ofcom, as the UK’s independent communications regulator, has a duty to secure alternative dispute resolution (ADR) schemes for domestic and small business customers to make sure their rights are upheld. Ofcom periodically reviews the two approved ADR schemes (Ombudsman Services: Communications and the Communications and Internet Services Adjudication Scheme) and monitors their ability to deal with complaints independently, transparently and effectively.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-25T08:35:31.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513602/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513602/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-18","Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment he has made of the (a) accountability of internet service providers to their customers and (b) role of the regulator in upholding the rights of those customers.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","34454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513603","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-22","<p>The provision of access services on video on demand content has increased in recent years, according to the 2015 Authority for Television on Demand report which can be found here: <a href="http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/broadcast/on-demand/access-european/AS_survey_report_2015.pdf" target="_blank">http://stakeholders.ofcom.org.uk/binaries/broadcast/on-demand/access-european/AS_survey_report_2015.pdf</a>. The evidence in this report is supported by dialogue with broadcasters, content providers and platform operators, who fed back to the Department of Culture, Media and Sport in Autumn 2015.</p><p /><p /> <p>Ofcom, the principle regulator for video on demand services, is reviewing how to improve the provision of access services on video on demand services.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-22T13:49:39.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513603/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513603/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-18","Video on Demand","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what assessment he has made of progress on increasing the provision of access services on video on demand content; what further proposals his Department has to improve progress in that area; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","34490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513604","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-26","<p>The number and location of Army Reserve deployments in the last 12 months are shown in the following table:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Location</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Personnel Number</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Afghanistan</p></td><td><p>65</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Algeria</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bahrain</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cyprus</p></td><td><p>175</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Egypt</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ethiopia</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Falkland Islands</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Iraq</p></td><td><p>35</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Italy</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jordan</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kenya</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Kuwait</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Latvia</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Malawi</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nigeria</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oman</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Senegal</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sudan</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sierra Leone</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Somalia</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Tunisia</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ukraine</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Uganda</p></td><td><p>~</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Rounding is necessary, as a means of disclosure control and the preservation of anonymity; it also improves the clarity of output and conveys an appropriate level of precision to users.</p><p>‘~’ is less than five.</p><p> </p><p>It is expected that reserve mobilisation is likely to double during 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Formed Reserve bodies will be deploying on some 23 overseas exercises this year; the majority of these will be at Company level. 4 PARA will also deploy for one rotation of the Falkland Islands Reinforcement Company in June-July 2016, while the intent is for 4 LANCS to be the Cyprus lead in October 2016.</p><p> </p>","Canterbury","Mr Julian Brazier",,"2016-04-26T16:07:58.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513604/answer","Biography information for Sir Julian Brazier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513604/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Army Reserve: Deployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the number and location of overseas deployments of Army Reserve personnel were in the last 12 months; and what assessment he has made of potential increases in the number of such deployments in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","34498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513605","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-22","<p>We are encouraging the EU counter-migration mission, Operation SOPHIA, to increase its role in tackling irregular migration across the Central Mediterranean. Indeed, earlier this week the EU Foreign Affairs Council agreed on the need to evaluate options for increasing SOPHIA's impact on human trafficking networks. This may include broader security support to the legitimate Libyan authorities, for example through potential capacity building. The UK currently has HMS ENTERPRISE deployed in support of Operation SOPHIA, and although we have no immediate plans to increase naval patrols in the Mediterranean, we are keeping our contribution under review as the operation's requirements change.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-04-22T13:08:38.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513605/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513605/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Mediterranean Sea: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, to what extent the Royal Navy plans to increase naval patrols in the Mediterranean to respond to the increase in attempted illegal crossings by migrants from North Africa.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","34501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513606","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-21","<p>Commanding Officers do not have the power to deal by summary hearing with the offences of sexual assault, voyeurism, sexual activity in a public lavatory or exposure. These charges can only be dealt with by Court Martial or Service Civilian Court.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-04-21T15:25:49.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513606/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513606/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Armed Forces: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many allegations of (a) sexual assault, (b) voyeurism, (c) sexual activity in a public lavatory and (d) exposure have been dealt with summarily by a commanding officer in each year since 2009.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","34437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513607","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-26","<p>As stated in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, our latest estimate is that manufacturing the four Successor submarines is likely to cost a total of £31 billion, including inflation over the lifetime of the programme. We will also set a contingency of £10 billion. The MOD budget for the Spending Review period published in Budget 2016 included this latest estimate for the relevant period.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","34406","2016-04-26T16:06:30.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513607/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513607/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what recent estimate he has made of the capital costs of (a) replacing the Vanguard fleet with four new Successor submarines and (b) other foreseeable elements within the Trident renewal project up to the late 2030's.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","34407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513608","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-26","<p>As stated in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, our latest estimate is that manufacturing the four Successor submarines is likely to cost a total of £31 billion, including inflation over the lifetime of the programme. We will also set a contingency of £10 billion. The MOD budget for the Spending Review period published in Budget 2016 included this latest estimate for the relevant period.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","34407","2016-04-26T16:06:30.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513608/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513608/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department's capital programme prepared for Budget 2016 included revised estimates for the Trident Successor project.","false","Biography information for Crispin Blunt","Reigate","Crispin Blunt","34406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513609","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-25","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 13 April 2016 to Question 33058 to the hon. Member for Barrow and Furness (John Woodcock).</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","34329","2016-04-25T15:53:04.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513609/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513609/answer","Hansard Extacts 13  April 2016.docx","Maritime Patrol Aircraft","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513609/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Military Aircraft","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how much support work there has been for the order for the Boeing Poseidon P-8A (a) by value and (b) by number of jobs that will be undertaken by employees (i) in the UK, (ii) in the US and (iii) elsewhere; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","34328"
