"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513611","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Ministry of Defence has a longstanding relationship with Saudi Arabia, including the provision of training and advice in a broad range of areas including International Humanitarian Law. The education and training courses which Saudi Arabian military personnel have completed includes courses such as Managing Defence in a Wider Security Context, the Strategic Leadership Programmes, and Initial Officer training courses. These courses expose Saudi military personnel to UK policy, and promote concepts of accountability, compliance with International Humanitarian Law and transparency. They are important in building skills which enable Saudi Arabia to deal appropriately with their own security problems, thereby contributing to regional security.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-04-22T13:09:02.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513611/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513611/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","Saudi Arabia: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what advice was provided by UK service personnel to the Saudi military prior to 8 May 2015 on international humanitarian law and the designation of civilian populated city regions as valid military targets.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","34356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513612","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-25","<p>In December 2003 a competition was launched to provide the Royal Navy with an improved defensive anti-surface warfare capability with the preference being for an automated 30mm gun system. A number of companies entered the competition, and the MSI 'Seahawk' system was eventually chosen on the basis of cost, capability and through life support. The MSI weapon system, now referred to as the Automated Small Calibre Gun (ASCG) System, was subsequently selected for fitting to HMS QUEEN ELIZABETH.</p><p>Four ASCGs will be fitted on QUEEN ELIZABETH.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","34412","2016-04-25T15:50:15.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513612/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513612/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what analysis his Department made of alternatives to the MSI-DSL 30mm gun for deployment on HMS Queen Elizabeth.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","34411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513613","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-25","<p>In December 2003 a competition was launched to provide the Royal Navy with an improved defensive anti-surface warfare capability with the preference being for an automated 30mm gun system. A number of companies entered the competition, and the MSI 'Seahawk' system was eventually chosen on the basis of cost, capability and through life support. The MSI weapon system, now referred to as the Automated Small Calibre Gun (ASCG) System, was subsequently selected for fitting to HMS QUEEN ELIZABETH.</p><p>Four ASCGs will be fitted on QUEEN ELIZABETH.</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","34411","2016-04-25T15:50:15.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513613/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513613/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many MSI-DSL 30mm guns will be mounted on HMS Queen Elizabeth.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","34412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513614","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-25","<p>When HMS OCEAN is withdrawn from service consideration will be given to the assets and equipment that may be transferred to other platforms to support the Royal Navy's amphibious capability.</p><p>It is too early to provide exact details of all the assets that will be transferred.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-04-25T15:49:33.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513614/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513614/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-18","HMS Ocean","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which assets will be transferred from HMS Ocean for use on other platforms when she is withdrawn from service.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","34413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513615","Department for Education","false","2016-05-03","<p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Education has given evidence to the Education Select Committee six times since she was appointed in July 2014.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-03T16:27:54.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513615/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513615/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Education Select Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many times she has attended public meetings of the Education  Committee since her appointment.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","34344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513616","Department for Education","false","2016-04-28","<p>On 7 April 2016 we announced that we will not be using the results of the reception baseline assessment carried out in 2015-16 as the starting point for measuring progress in the accountability system. When this year’s reception classes leave primary school in 2022, we will continue to use Key Stage 1 (KS1) as the starting point from which to measure pupils’ progress to Key Stage 2 (KS2). The link to the announcement can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/reception-baseline-comparability-study-published" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/reception-baseline-comparability-study-published</a></p><p> </p><p>As announced in March 2014, the Early Years Foundation Stage Profile – an assessment at the end of Reception – will no longer be compulsory from September 2016. The Early Years Foundation Stage will continue to be statutory; supporting children to experience a broad and engaging programme of learning in reception.</p><p> </p><p>We know that assessment in reception is essential. Early years are critical to a child’s development and we want to ensure that teachers are able to identify where pupils may need additional support as early as possible. We remain committed to assessment in reception and that is why we are giving schools the option to use the baseline assessments as on-entry assessments in academic year 2016-17. The outcomes from these assessments will not be used for school accountability.</p><p> </p><p>We remain committed to the assessment of pupils through primary school. Over the coming months we will be looking at assessment arrangements in reception beyond 2016-17 and will engage stakeholders in that work.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-28T14:51:25.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513616/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513616/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Primary Education: Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on assessment of children in their reception year.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","34331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513617","Department for Education","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Government remains fully committed to ensuring pupils receive a well-rounded education. All state-funded schools must provide a broad and balanced curriculum that promotes the spiritual, moral, cultural, mental and physical development of pupils. We expect that all pupils should have the opportunity to study a range of subjects at primary and secondary school, including creative subjects.</p><p> </p><p>The EBacc is intended to be studied as part of a broad and balanced curriculum at Key Stage 4. It has been designed to be limited in size to provide a rigorous academic core whilst leaving space in the curriculum for other subjects. On average, pupils in state-funded schools enter nine GCSEs and equivalent qualifications, rising to more than ten for more able pupils. This information is available in the school and college performance tables found at <a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/performance/" target="_blank">http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/performance/</a>. For many pupils, taking the EBacc will equate to seven GCSEs; and for those taking triple science, it will equate to eight. This means that there will continue to be room to study other subjects, including expressive arts. The proportion of pupils in state-funded schools taking at least one GCSE in an arts subject has increased since the EBacc was first introduced, rising from 46% in 2011 to 50% in 2015.[1]</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473178/EBacc_and_non-EBacc_subject_entries_and_achievement.pdf" target="_blank">Statistical release: EBacc and non-EBacc subject entries and achievement: 2010/11 to 2014/15</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-28T14:53:19.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513617/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513617/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","GCSE","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that GCSE students are able to study expressive arts subjects alongside those subjects included in the English Baccalaurate; and whether studying such subjects will require taking more than the current average number of GCSEs taken in England.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","34332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513618","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>We have protected public services, including education, in all of our trade agreements and will continue to do so in the EU-US free trade agreement, also known as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership (TTIP). This is non-negotiable.</p><p>The Government remains committed to providing the best quality education for all children and young people. TTIP will not change this. The government of the day, not our trade partners, will always set the rules governing how the education system is run.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-25T14:49:14.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513618/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513618/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-18","Education: Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether education will be exempt from the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership agreement; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","34354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513619","Department for Education","false","2016-04-26","<p>Tackling obesity, particularly in children, is one of our major priorities. We will be launching our cross-government Childhood Obesity Strategy in the summer. It will look at everything that contributes to a child becoming overweight and obese. It will also set out what more can be done by all.</p><p>The School Food Standards apply to all local authority maintained schools and to academies that opened prior to 2010 and from June 2014 onwards.</p><p>1,420 academies have voluntarily registered to follow the standards, including some of the largest Multi-Academy Trusts. Many academy caterers also hold the Food for Life Catering Mark, which also guarantees compliance with the School Food Standards.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-04-26T16:15:46.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513619/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513619/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to assess the potential benefits of applying school food standards to all schools as part of the Government's childhood obesity strategy.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","34430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513620","Department for Education","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Department for Education uses the Teacher Supply Model (TSM) to estimate the national requirements for the primary phase and each secondary subject for the number of postgraduate Initial Teacher Training places to meet future demand. The model also estimates the number of qualified teachers that will be in active service and the number that will enter into active service (either as Newly Qualified Teachers or those that qualified more than one year beforehand) for each year. The table below shows the number of qualified teachers that will be in active service each year and the number that will enter active service each year as estimated by the 2016/17 TSM:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2017/18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2018/19</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2019/20</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2020/21</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p><strong>Estimated no. of qualified teachers in active service (headcount)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Primary</strong></p></td><td><p>238,215</p></td><td><p>240,267</p></td><td><p>241,708</p></td><td><p>243,027</p></td><td><p>243,447</p></td><td><p>244,048</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Secondary</strong></p></td><td><p>216,284</p></td><td><p>217,681</p></td><td><p>219,268</p></td><td><p>221,456</p></td><td><p>223,722</p></td><td><p>225,540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>454,499</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>457,948</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>460,976</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>464,483</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>467,169</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>469,588</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td rowspan="3"><p><strong>Estimated no. of qualified teachers entering active service (headcount)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Primary</strong></p></td><td><p>27,159</p></td><td><p>26,622</p></td><td><p>26,117</p></td><td><p>26,080</p></td><td><p>25,342</p></td><td><p>25,464</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Secondary</strong></p></td><td><p>23,385</p></td><td><p>24,033</p></td><td><p>24,094</p></td><td><p>24,526</p></td><td><p>24,550</p></td><td><p>24,234</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>50,544</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>50,655</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>50,211</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>50,606</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>49,892</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>49,697</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: 2016/17 Teacher Supply Model</em></p><p>The 2016/17 TSM, along with a user guide explaining the methodology in detail, is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/teacher-supply-model</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-22T13:56:41.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513620/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513620/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Teachers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the number of teachers (a) actively seeking or in teaching employment by 2020 and (b) needed in such employment by that date; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","34458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513621","Department for Education","false","2016-04-26","<p>We have not reduced the allocation of top-up funding for children with special educational needs (SEN). We announced in December that we would provide an additional £92.5 million nationally for high needs in 2016-17. Bristol City Council’s share of this additional funding is £750,000.</p><p>It is for local authorities to determine how best to use their high needs allocation, after consultation with local providers.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-04-26T16:15:27.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513621/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513621/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Special Educational Needs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons the Government decided to reduce the allocation of top-up funding for provision for children with special needs.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","34459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513622","Department for Education","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) is continuing to make excellent progress to transform the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement experiences for young people, including growing its Enterprise Advisers Network. The CEC is responsible for the administrative resources provided to the network. We therefore suggest contacting the company directly for detailed information about the network, including regions to which Enterprise Co-ordinators and Advisers have been appointed. The CEC can be contacted at <a href="mailto:info@careersandenterprise.co.uk" target="_blank">info@careersandenterprise.co.uk</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","34505","2016-04-21T15:51:25.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513622/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513622/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Enterprise Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 30445, to which regions the 173 volunteer Enterprise Advisers have been appointed.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","34504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513623","Department for Education","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Careers &amp; Enterprise Company (CEC) is continuing to make excellent progress to transform the provision of careers, enterprise and employer engagement experiences for young people, including growing its Enterprise Advisers Network. The CEC is responsible for the administrative resources provided to the network. We therefore suggest contacting the company directly for detailed information about the network, including regions to which Enterprise Co-ordinators and Advisers have been appointed. The CEC can be contacted at <a href="mailto:info@careersandenterprise.co.uk" target="_blank">info@careersandenterprise.co.uk</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","34504","2016-04-21T15:51:25.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513623/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513623/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Enterprise Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 March 2016 to Question 30445, to which regions the 50 Enterprise Coordinators have been appointed.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","34505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513624","Department for Education","false","2016-04-26","<p>Over 5,200 families received support from the Adoption Support Fund during 2015-16. We estimate that around 6,000 families will be supported in 2016-17 rising to around 8,000 in 2017-18.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2016-04-26T16:27:42.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513624/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513624/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment she has made of the level of need for therapeutic support for children following abuse or neglect referred to in her Department's report, entitled Adoption: A vision for change, published in March 2016.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","34517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513625","Department for Education","false","2016-04-28","<p>The Department for Education does not collect data on the proportion of primary school pupils having access to music lessons with a specialist music teacher within their school curriculum. Schools are best placed to decide on the number and type of teachers they need.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016-17, we are investing £75 million in music education hubs to ensure all pupils aged 5-18 have access to high quality musical opportunities. Primary schools can access support from specialist music teachers through music education hubs. In 2013/14, Arts Council England data showed that 596,820 pupils learned to play an instrument through whole class ensemble teaching, up from 531,422 in 2012/13.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-28T15:22:59.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513625/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513625/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-18","Music: Primary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of primary school pupils have access to music lessons with a specialist music teacher within their school.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","34456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513626","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-25","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's position, as set out by my rt. hon. Friend the Prime Minister to the House on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p> </p><p>We currently expect our electricity interconnector capacity with Europe to double by the early 2020s with studies showing they could deliver benefits to British consumers of almost £12 billion over 25 years. As the White Paper that the Government published in February on the process for withdrawing from the European Union makes clear, a vote to leave the EU would lead to a prolonged period of uncertainty, including on the nature of our access to the EU's single energy market.</p><p> </p>","Hastings and Rye","Amber Rudd",,"2016-04-25T10:34:48.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513626/answer","Biography information for Amber Rudd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513626/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Electricity Interconnectors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department has prepared contingency plans relating to interconnection with the continental electricity grid in the event of the UK voting to leave the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","34442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513627","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State announced in her speech on 18 November that the Department will be launching a consultation to close all coal fired power stations. A consultation will be launched shortly.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T11:34:30.883Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513627/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513627/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513627/answer/previousversion/56733","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Coal Fired Power Stations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when she plans to open her Department's consultation on the timetable for closing all coal-fired power stations in the UK.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","34471"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513628","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>Energy security is my top priority. The Department will take the steps needed to ensure hard working families and business have the energy they need, including from overseas where this adds to the diversity and cost effectiveness of our energy supplies.</p><p> </p><p>Interconnection provides greater security of supply as we import from a diverse generation mix, allowing us to access, for example, Norway’s large amounts of hydropower.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has an open and competitive gas market in which gas is traded freely. Gas enters the UK system from a range of sources including the UK Continental Shelf, Norway, the Netherlands and Belgium, as well as the LNG imports. This diverse and flexible range of domestic and foreign supplies ensures security of supply, encourages competition and helps to lower energy costs for British consumers and industry.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T13:43:29.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513628/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513628/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, if her Department will take steps to ensure that (a) the UK is energy secure and independent and (b) reliance on foreign gas supplies and cross border electrical connections coupled with decommissioning of UK energy resources does not result in an energy shortage in the UK in the next 10 years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","34515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513629","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>Nearly £52 billion has been invested in renewables since 2010. The average annual investment in renewables has more than doubled in the last 5 years, with an average of £9bn invested each year in UK-based renewables. Indeed, 2015 was another record year with £13bn invested in renewable electricity.</p><p> </p><p>In order to support further investment in renewables, we announced in the 2016 Budget funding for three further Contracts For Difference allocation rounds, worth £730m of annual support. We have also announced that the Renewable Heat Incentive budget will continue to March 2021, when it will reach £1.15 billion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T13:42:39.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513629/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513629/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what steps she is taking to tackle the reduction in investment for renewable energy projected between 2017 to 2020 in the most recent National Infrastructure Pipeline, published on 23 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","34502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513630","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>The UK is already playing its part in delivering the Paris climate deal, through its contribution to meeting EU climate and energy targets and through its domestic climate framework set out in the Climate Change Act. In addition, the Government believes we need to take the step of enshrining the global goal of net zero greenhouse gas emissions into UK law. As a first step, our independent advisors, the Committee on Climate Change, are looking at the implications of the Paris commitments. The Committee has said that it will report in the autumn, and we will consider carefully the recommendations.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T11:34:55.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513630/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513630/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513630/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513630/answer/previousversion/56732","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Climate Change Convention: Paris","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what progress the Government has made on its commitment to enshrine the Paris climate deal into UK law.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","34423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513631","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Contract for Difference mechanism provides increased price certainty to generators regardless of wholesale electricity sale prices, thereby incentivising investment in low carbon generation. It does this by paying the generator the difference between the strike price and the market reference price (a composite of wholesale price indices) for electricity sold into the market for the duration of the contract. The generator will make difference payments back to the Low Carbon Contracts Company should the market reference price rise above the strike price.</p><p> </p><p>The strike price for the Hinkley Point C project was agreed in October 2013 and is £92.50/MWh. If EDF take a Final Investment Decision in relation to Sizewell C, the strike price for Hinkley Point C will be reduced to £89.50/MWh.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T11:33:26.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513631/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513631/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513631/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513631/answer/previousversion/56731","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Hinkley Point C Power Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the potential merits of raising the level of support offered through the Contract for Difference for Hinkley Point C as a result of low wholesale energy prices.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","34362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513632","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Government is committed to making energy more affordable, supporting a more competitive, innovative, and smarter energy system that drives down bills. At the last Autumn Statement, the government also set out action to reduce the projected impact of policies on average household energy bills by around £30 a year from 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Department intends to publish, in due course, an update on the projected costs of policies funded through supplier levies and obligations that impact consumer energy bills. In addition, the department continues to assess the impact of individual policy proposals on the energy bills of various consumers (including households and businesses), which it sets out in relevant policy impact assessments, available online at <a href="http://www.gov.uk/" target="_blank">www.gov.uk</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T11:34:01.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513632/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513632/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513632/answer","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513632/answer/previousversion/56730","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when her Department will publish its most recent assessment of the effect of energy and climate change policies on energy prices and bills.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","34361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513633","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>Any new coal plant must demonstrate carbon capture and storage on at least 300 MW of its proposed generating capacity and comply with the Emissions Performance Standard. The Department will be launching a consultation on closing unabated coal-fired power stations and will ask for views on what measures might be suitable for existing coal.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T13:40:13.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513633/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513633/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513633/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Coal Fired Power Stations: Electricity Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what her Department's definition is of abated coal-fired electricity generation; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","34355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513634","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>Oil and Gas UK in the <em>UK Continental Shelf Offshore Workforce Demographics Report 2015</em> estimate that of the total number of offshore workers resident in the UK, 13.8 per cent (7,711) live in the North East of England.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T13:47:11.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513634/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513634/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513634/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Offshore Industry: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what estimate she has made of the number of people from the North East of England working offshore in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","34352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513635","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>Petroleum Exploration and Development Licence 189 carries an Initial Term Work Programme to obtain and reprocess seismic data and to drill a well. The seismic data has been acquired and reprocessed. The operator has requested from the Oil and Gas Authority an amendment of the licence to allow additional time for the drilling of the well.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T13:44:28.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513635/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513635/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513635/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Oil: Exploration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether the firm work commitments relating to Petroleum Exploration and Development Licence 189 which expire on 30 June 2016 have been satisfied.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513636","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-22","<p>A deed of variation has not been agreed for this licence.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-22T13:44:50.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513636/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513636/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513636/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-18","Oil: Exploration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether a deed of variation has been agreed for Petroleum Exploration and Development Licence 189.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","34369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513637","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-21","<p>Defra has funded a project, undertaken by the University of Plymouth, to study the effects of microplastics in the marine environment. The project studied whether chemical pollutants stick to plastic particles, whether marine organisms ingest plastic particles and pass them along the food chain, and whether the plastics themselves, or associated chemical pollutants, could cause harm to those organisms. The final report for this project is expected to be published shortly.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-04-21T10:31:13.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513637/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513637/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513637/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Marine Environment: Plastics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the effect of microbeads on marine ecosystems.","false","Biography information for Mr David Jones","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","34315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513638","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-27","<p>As of 31 March 2016, the Rural Payments Agency had paid 168 (80%) of the 211 eligible Basic Payment Scheme 2015 claims received in Stafford constituency. To date 191 had been paid and the agency has announced that those customers who do not receive a claim payment in April will be provided a bridging payment. Bridging payments will be around half of their claim value.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","34306","2016-04-27T13:33:30.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513638/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513638/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513638/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many farmers in Stafford constituency who are eligible for payments under the Basic Payments Scheme 2015 had not been paid by 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","34305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513639","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-27","<p>As of 31 March 2016, the Rural Payments Agency had paid 168 (80%) of the 211 eligible Basic Payment Scheme 2015 claims received in Stafford constituency. To date 191 had been paid and the agency has announced that those customers who do not receive a claim payment in April will be provided a bridging payment. Bridging payments will be around half of their claim value.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","34305","2016-04-27T13:33:30.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513639/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513639/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513639/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Agriculture: Subsidies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many payments under the Basic Payments Scheme 2015 had not been made to farmers in Stafford constituency by the Rural Payments Agency by 31 March 2016.","false","Biography information for Jeremy Lefroy","Stafford","Jeremy Lefroy","34306"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513640","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-26","<p>The Department does not expect to pay any penalties and disallowances imposed by the EU Commission in relation to air pollution in 2016-2017.</p><p> </p><p>The Commission has started infraction proceedings against the UK for not achieving European limit values for NO<sub>2</sub>. We want to work in partnership with Local Authorities and the Commission to improve air quality and avoid any prospect of fines levied from infraction. In December 2015, the Government published air quality plans setting out a comprehensive approach for meeting EU legal limits in the shortest possible time through a new programme of Clean Air Zones, alongside national action and continued investment in clean technologies. The UK has never had to pay an infraction fine.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-04-26T10:57:41.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513640/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513640/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513640/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Air Pollution: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what amount her Department expects to pay in penalties and disallowances required by the EU Commission in relation to air pollution in 2016-17; and what contingency has been made for that purpose in her Department's budget.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bridgen","North West Leicestershire","Andrew Bridgen","34390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513641","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-26","<p>The effects of climate change continue to be taken into account within policy making across Defra and all levels of Government and within the broad range of related communications activities. Targeted communications closely tied to specific climate threats help those affected to understand potential impacts and the practical actions that they can take to increase their resilience and adapt. For instance, the Environment Agency have been ‘geo-targeting’ people in specific high flood risk locations via Facebook and other services to promote the benefits of and sign up to the free flood warning service.</p><p> </p><p>Government will be publishing the second UK Climate Change Risk Assessment in 2017 to be followed by the second National Adaptation Programme report and will, as part of that process, consider the need for further public communications on the effects of climate change in the UK.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-04-26T11:05:33.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513641/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513641/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513641/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Climate Change: Publicity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has for public communications on the need to prepare for the effects of climate change.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","34443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513642","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-21","<p>Adaptation is embedded as an integral part of policy making across Defra and all levels of Government and within a broad range of programmes and activities that directly or indirectly support and build the UK’s resilience to climate change. The first National Adaptation Programme sets out more than 370 actions to help the UK better prepare for climate change and we continue to deliver on these actions. In Defra we are taking action across the breadth of the department’s policies, from our £2.3 billion flood defence programme to the Forestry Commission increasing the diversity of its planting stock so that the Public Forest Estate is resilient to the changing climate.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-04-21T10:40:09.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513642/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513642/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513642/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what funding her Department has allocated for (a) 2016-17 and (b) 2017-18 to help the UK prepare for the effects of climate change.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","34472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513643","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The UN Mission in South Sudan (UNMISS) has had significant effect in protecting civilians, most notably the 200,000 internally displaced persons who have sought shelter on its bases. However, the mission faces a number of challenges, not least continued obstruction and access restrictions by the parties to the conflict. The UK will continue to work with UNMISS to improve the effectiveness of the mission’s operations and is working with the UN to finalise the new military deployment of 250 - 300 British troops to the Mission announced by the Prime Minister, my right hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), in September 2015.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-21T11:19:52.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513643/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513643/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513643/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","South Sudan: Peacekeeping Operations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of UN missions in South Sudan in protecting civilians in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","34482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513644","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>Medical personnel and facilities are entitled to respect and protection under specific provisions in international humanitarian law. We are concerned at the growing number of attacks on medical personnel and facilities in conflict situations. The UK is working with other members of the Security Council on a draft resolution on this issue, and it hopes that a text emerges that all Council members can support. The UK would like the text to reinforce the need for the humanitarian principles of humanity, neutrality, impartiality and independence in the provision of humanitarian assistance to be respected.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-04-21T11:22:37.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513644/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513644/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513644/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Armed Conflict: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if the Government will support the draft UN resolution on protection of medical facilities in conflict and investigations into incidents when such facilities are attacked.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","34483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513645","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The British High Commission in Delhi is closely following the situation in Kashmir. I was saddened to learn of the deaths of 5 civilians last week and I extend my condolences to their families. I am aware that the State Government and the Army are both looking into these incidents. I have not recently discussed Kashmir with other Commonwealth countries.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-26T14:06:28.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513645/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513645/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513645/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Kashmir: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with other Commonwealth countries on recent unrest in the Handwara and Kupwara districts of Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","34380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513646","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) has discussed this issue with the French Foreign Minister and also with Ambassador Pierre Vimont, the French Special Envoy for the Middle East Peace Process. British officials have also regularly discussed the initiative with their French counterparts.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-21T14:58:40.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513646/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513646/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513646/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his French counterpart on initiatives by that government to convene a peace conference on the Israel-Palestine conflict.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","34382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513647","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The UK Government has paid out around £21m at current prices. This comprises two sums. An initial figure of £650,000 which the UK Government paid in 1973 to the Government of Mauritius towards the resettlement of those removed from the British Indian Ocean Territory since 1965. This was disbursed with accrued interest in 1977 and 1978 to 595 families. Furthermore, in 1982 the UK Government paid over a further £4m pursuant to an agreement with the Government of Mauritius which had established the Ilois Trust Fund Board to distribute the money for the benefit of the Chagossians. The government of Mauritius had also contributed some land to the Trust Fund and the government of India contributed £1m to it. At least 1,344 Chagossians received compensation through the Trust Fund, which was largely paid out between 1982 and 1984, with a final disbursement in 1987. The Government does not hold information about those it has not compensated.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","34397","2016-04-21T14:34:05.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513647/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513647/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513647/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many Chagossian families have not received any compensation from the public purse.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","34395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513648","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>The UK Government has paid out around £21m at current prices. This comprises two sums. An initial figure of £650,000 which the UK Government paid in 1973 to the Government of Mauritius towards the resettlement of those removed from the British Indian Ocean Territory since 1965. This was disbursed with accrued interest in 1977 and 1978 to 595 families. Furthermore, in 1982 the UK Government paid over a further £4m pursuant to an agreement with the Government of Mauritius which had established the Ilois Trust Fund Board to distribute the money for the benefit of the Chagossians. The government of Mauritius had also contributed some land to the Trust Fund and the government of India contributed £1m to it. At least 1,344 Chagossians received compensation through the Trust Fund, which was largely paid out between 1982 and 1984, with a final disbursement in 1987. The Government does not hold information about those it has not compensated.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","34395","2016-04-21T14:34:05.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513648/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513648/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513648/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much compensation was paid from the public purse to Chagossians; on what dates such compensation payments were made; and how many families were so compensated.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","34397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513649","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>Due to ongoing legal action against the Government, I regret that I am unable to respond to the question at this stage. As soon as matters are concluded, I shall write to the Hon. Gentleman with an answer to his question.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-04-21T14:05:40.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513649/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513649/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Ilois: Resettlement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much compensation was paid from the public purse to Chagossians who were deported to the Seychelles.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","34396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513650","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>I am not aware of any invitations to the government to meet Mr Bancoult during his recent visit to the UK. Officials who were asked whether they might wish to meet Mr Bancoult were concerned about the propriety and appropriateness of doing so at a time when he is litigating against the Government.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-04-21T14:06:32.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513650/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513650/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Chagos Refugees Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, for what reasons the Government did not meet Olivier Bancoult, Chair of the Chagos Refugees Group, during his recent visit to the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","34398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513651","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>We are aware of media reporting on this issue. No assessment has been made.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-04-21T14:35:52.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513651/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513651/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Israel: Intelligence Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what reports he has received of plans by the Israeli government to use its security services to disrupt and gather information on supporters of a boycott of Israel; and if he will make an assessment of the potential effects of such plans on UK citizens.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","34399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513652","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-26","I was saddened to learn of the deaths of 5 civilians last week in Northern Kashmir, and I extend my condolences to their families. I have not discussed this issue with the Indian Government or with other Commonwealth Countries, but I am aware that the State Government and the Army are both looking into these incidents.","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-26T14:10:00.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513652/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513652/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513652/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Kashmir: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Indian government on the need to de-escalate tensions between the Indian army and protestors in Northern Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","34371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513653","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>The British High Commission in Delhi is closely following the situation in Kashmir. I welcome the recent formation of a new State Government.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-04-26T14:16:59.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513653/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513653/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513653/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-04-18","Kashmir: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the political situation in Kashmir.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","34370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513654","Department of Health","false","2016-04-25","<p>Attendance at Committee meetings is a matter of public record and is dependent on a request from the Committee. My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has attended five public meetings with the Health Committee.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-25T11:25:11.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513654/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513654/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513654/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Health Select Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many times he has attended public meetings with the Health Committee since his appointment.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","34345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513655","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>The level of provision of infertility treatment, as for all health services they commission, is decided by local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and will take into account the needs of the population overall. The CCG’s decisions are underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs. As such, provision of services will vary in response to local needs.</p><p>NHS England expects that all those involved in commissioning infertility treatment services to be fully aware of the importance of having regard to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) fertility guidelines. CCGs have a legal duty to have regard to NICE guidelines.</p><p>Following a meeting with Fertility Fairness in December 2015, officials from the Department and NHS England are considering options for addressing variation in the prices that CCGs are currently paying for in vitro fertilisation treatment.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34409","2016-04-26T10:31:06.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513655/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513655/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513655/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Fertility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the availability of fertility treatments under each clinical commissioning group in England.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","34410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513656","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>Where a general practitioner (GP) practice wishes to remove a patient from their list the contract, between the practice and NHS England, requires practices to have reasonable grounds for doing so. The contract also requires practices to have notified the patient in the preceding 12 months that they are at risk of removal from the list and explained the reasons for this.</p><p>Practices must notify NHS England and the patient of the intended removal and the reasons for the removal. It is the responsibility of NHS England to notify the patient that they will be, or have been, removed from their practice’s list of patients. Removal from the list will take place on the eighth day after NHS England receive notification of the removal or the date on which NHS England are notified that the patient has registered with another GP practice.</p><p>Where a patient is receiving treatment at intervals of less than seven days, the removal will take place on the eighth day after treatment is no longer needed or the date on which NHS England receives notification that the patient has registered with another practice.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-21T14:03:17.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513656/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513656/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513656/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what safeguards are in place to ensure that patients are not removed from patient registers without their prior knowledge.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","34317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513657","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) collects sampling data from local authorities on an annual basis. Food standards sampling is the responsibility of county councils, unitary authorities, the London Boroughs and some but not all metropolitan borough councils. Sampling for food standards covers analyses for chemical (other) contamination, composition, and labelling and presentation.</p><p> </p><p>Sampling data, including for food standards, and total numbers of samples taken for 2012/13, 2013/14 and 2014/15, as reported by local authorities, are published on the FSA’s website at the links below. All of the food standards samples reported would have been submitted for analysis to the public analyst appointed by the individual local authorities. The data at the links covers food standards samples paid for by FSA and those paid for by the local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>2014/15 - <a href="http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-uk-sampling-data-2014-15.xlsx" target="_blank">www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-uk-sampling-data-2014-15.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>2013/14 - <a href="http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-sampling-data-2013-14.xls" target="_blank">www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-sampling-data-2013-14.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>2012/13 - <a href="http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/multimedia/spreadsheets/laems-sampling_2012-13.xls" target="_blank">www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/multimedia/spreadsheets/laems-sampling_2012-13.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>Local authorities with responsibility for food standards that did not report sampling in 2012/13, 2013/14 and 2014/15 are shown below.</p><p> </p><p>2014/15 - Isles of Scilly</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 - Isles of Scilly, Sutton, Blackpool, Rutland</p><p> </p><p>2012/13 - Isles of Scilly, Birmingham, Rochdale, Blackburn, Rutland, Leicester City, Swindon, South Lanarkshire and Armagh</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Where the FSA pays for a local authority to take a sample, and its analysis, FSA requires that the data on the sample is reported on the UK Food Surveillance System. Total figures for each period are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total United Kingdom food standards samples taken by local authorities</p></td><td><p>33,431</p></td><td><p>36,710</p></td><td><p>24,286</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total UK food standards samples funded by FSA</p></td><td><p>2,936</p></td><td><p>5,683</p></td><td><p>6,243</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total UK food standards samples funded by local authorities</p></td><td><p>30,495</p></td><td><p>31,027</p></td><td><p>18,043</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34310","2016-04-21T14:22:07.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513657/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513657/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513657/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Food: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many reports of food standards sampling were submitted to each local authority's appointed public analyst in (a) 2012-13, (b) 2013-14 and (c) 2014-15; how many of those reports submitted to the public analyst were taken as part of a Food Standards Agency-funded project; and how many of those reports were paid for by the local authority.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513658","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The National Congenital Anomaly and Rare Disease Registration Service (NCARDRS) is operated by Public Health England. NCARDRS has legal permission to collect patient identifiable data without the need for individual consent. As part of this dataset, patient postcodes for individuals resident in England are recorded on the NCARDRS congenital anomaly database. Protection of individual patient data is paramount and release of this data, including postcode data, is strictly controlled.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-04-21T07:59:54.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513658/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513658/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513658/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Congenital Abnormalities: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the postcodes for the addresses of mothers of babies born with congenital abnormalities are available on the British Isles Network of Congenital Anomaly Registers.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","34325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513659","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>Information on the number of live births affected by congenital abnormalities including spina bifida, hydrocephalus and anencephaly has been collected by the British Isles Network of Congenital Anomaly Registers and is currently available for the years 2009–2012 at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.binocar.org/publications/reports" target="_blank">http://www.binocar.org/publications/reports</a></p><p> </p><p>There are no current mechanisms in place for monitoring the take-up of advice given on the NHS Choices website about preventing spina bifida.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34322","2016-04-21T15:27:05.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513659/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513659/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513659/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Spina Bifida","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what procedures are in place to monitor the take-up of advice on NHS websites on prevention of spina bifida.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","34323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513660","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-21","<p>Wheat flour is the only food with mandatory fortification requirements in the UK. All wheat flour (except wholemeal) is required to be fortified with calcium, iron, niacin and thiamin at specific levels prescribed in the Bread and Flour Regulations 1998.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-04-21T10:34:55.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513660/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513660/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513660/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-18","Food: Additives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many staple foods in the UK are subject to mandatory fortification.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","34324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513661","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>Information on the number of live births affected by congenital abnormalities including spina bifida, hydrocephalus and anencephaly has been collected by the British Isles Network of Congenital Anomaly Registers and is currently available for the years 2009–2012 at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.binocar.org/publications/reports" target="_blank">http://www.binocar.org/publications/reports</a></p><p> </p><p>There are no current mechanisms in place for monitoring the take-up of advice given on the NHS Choices website about preventing spina bifida.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34323","2016-04-21T15:27:05.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513661/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513661/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513661/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Congenital Abnormalities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many live births of children affected by (a) spina bifida, (b) hydrocephaly and (c) anencephaly there have been in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","34322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513662","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Food Standards Agency (FSA) collects sampling data from local authorities on an annual basis. Food standards sampling is the responsibility of county councils, unitary authorities, the London Boroughs and some but not all metropolitan borough councils. Sampling for food standards covers analyses for chemical (other) contamination, composition, and labelling and presentation.</p><p> </p><p>Sampling data, including for food standards, and total numbers of samples taken for 2012/13, 2013/14 and 2014/15, as reported by local authorities, are published on the FSA’s website at the links below. All of the food standards samples reported would have been submitted for analysis to the public analyst appointed by the individual local authorities. The data at the links covers food standards samples paid for by FSA and those paid for by the local authorities.</p><p> </p><p>2014/15 - <a href="http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-uk-sampling-data-2014-15.xlsx" target="_blank">www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-uk-sampling-data-2014-15.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>2013/14 - <a href="http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-sampling-data-2013-14.xls" target="_blank">www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/laems-sampling-data-2013-14.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>2012/13 - <a href="http://www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/multimedia/spreadsheets/laems-sampling_2012-13.xls" target="_blank">www.food.gov.uk/sites/default/files/multimedia/spreadsheets/laems-sampling_2012-13.xls</a></p><p> </p><p>Local authorities with responsibility for food standards that did not report sampling in 2012/13, 2013/14 and 2014/15 are shown below.</p><p> </p><p>2014/15 - Isles of Scilly</p><p> </p><p>2013/14 - Isles of Scilly, Sutton, Blackpool, Rutland</p><p> </p><p>2012/13 - Isles of Scilly, Birmingham, Rochdale, Blackburn, Rutland, Leicester City, Swindon, South Lanarkshire and Armagh</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Where the FSA pays for a local authority to take a sample, and its analysis, FSA requires that the data on the sample is reported on the UK Food Surveillance System. Total figures for each period are shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total United Kingdom food standards samples taken by local authorities</p></td><td><p>33,431</p></td><td><p>36,710</p></td><td><p>24,286</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total UK food standards samples funded by FSA</p></td><td><p>2,936</p></td><td><p>5,683</p></td><td><p>6,243</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total UK food standards samples funded by local authorities</p></td><td><p>30,495</p></td><td><p>31,027</p></td><td><p>18,043</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34311","2016-04-21T14:22:07.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513662/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513662/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513662/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Food: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which local authorities did not report any food standards sampling in 2012-13, 2013-14 and 2014-15 via the Local Authority Monitoring System; and how many samples were taken by each local authority that took at least one sample.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","34310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513663","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>Health Education England (HEE) is committed to supporting a range of vocational based learning programmes, including the healthcare cadet apprenticeships in the North West.</p><p>Health Education England North West make approximately 400 places available through the programme every year. HEE undertook an extensive consultation with National Health Service trusts and dental practices, about the Healthcare Cadet Scheme. On the basis of the feedback received, HEE decided to close the programme and have developed a new model for vocational training to start in April 2017.</p><p>Healthcare cadetships are available in other areas. No data is collected centrally on these.</p><p>There are several Healthcare Cadet apprenticeship schemes in operation across England. No data is available on national spending on these schemes. No national assessment has been made on the effectiveness of Healthcare Cadet schemes.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","34417 ; 34418","2016-04-21T10:30:25.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513663/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513663/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513663/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","NHS: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Healthcare Cadet scheme.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","34419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513664","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>The level of provision of infertility treatment, as for all health services they commission, is decided by local clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) and will take into account the needs of the population overall. The CCG’s decisions are underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs. As such, provision of services will vary in response to local needs.</p><p>NHS England expects that all those involved in commissioning infertility treatment services to be fully aware of the importance of having regard to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) fertility guidelines. CCGs have a legal duty to have regard to NICE guidelines.</p><p>Following a meeting with Fertility Fairness in December 2015, officials from the Department and NHS England are considering options for addressing variation in the prices that CCGs are currently paying for in vitro fertilisation treatment.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","34410","2016-04-26T10:31:06.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513664/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513664/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513664/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Fertility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department has issued to clinical commissioning groups on the provision and availability of fertility treatments.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","34409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513665","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>All National Health Service providers of regulated activities have to register with the Care Quality Commission (CQC) and follow a set of fundamental standards of safety and quality below which care should never fall. One of the fundamental standards relates to staffing and requires that a provider must have sufficient numbers of suitability qualified, competent, skilled and experienced persons in order to meet the requirements of residents.</p><p> </p><p>The CQC has a wide range of enforcement powers that it can use if the provider is not does not meet the fundamental standards.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-04-21T10:30:22.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513665/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513665/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513665/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Hospitals: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, for how many hospital shifts a full complement of staff was not available in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","34420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513666","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-21T14:01:34.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513666/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513666/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513666/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","General Practitioners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of people removed without notification from GP practice patient registers in (a) Lewisham, Deptford constituency and (b) Greater Manchester in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","34318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513667","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>NHS England advises that the High Weald Lewes Havens Clinical Commissioning Group (CCG), on behalf of all seven Sussex CCGs, has begun an enquiry on 18 April 2016 into the non-emergency Patient Transport Service (PTS) in Sussex.</p><p> </p><p>We are informed that the CCG has engaged TIAA, an independent company and a provider of assurance services to the public sector, to carry out the enquiry. This is an independent investigation into the transition and mobilisation of the PTS contract from the South East Coast Ambulance Service to Coperforma and is supported by the CCGs in Sussex, Coperforma and the South East Coast Ambulance Service. We are advised the CCG has asked for a draft final report to be available for review by June 2016 with interim progress reports.</p><p> </p><p>We are advised the following terms of reference have been agreed by South East Coast Ambulance Service, High Weald Lewes Havens CCG and Coperforma:</p><p>― consideration of the transition arrangements set out in such as contract specification and tender submission;</p><p>― the extent to which compliance with agreed handover arrangements can be evidenced;</p><p>― a root cause analysis of a sample of incomplete bookings;</p><p>― establishing the causes of poor service delivery on commencement of the new contract and whether these could have been reasonably anticipated prior to the contract commencement date;</p><p>― the appropriateness and timeliness of the actions taken by the CCG; and</p><p>― any lesson learned which could be incorporated into other future major contracts let by the CCG.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-04-26T16:42:23.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513667/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513667/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513667/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Hospitals: Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what reports he has received on the NHS investigation into the performance of the non-urgent transport service provided by Coperforma in Sussex; who will conduct that investigation; what the terms of reference and expected duration of that investigation are; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","34414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513668","Department of Health","false","2016-04-26","<p>The current dental contract reform prototypes are testing a new way of providing preventative care, including the right balance of payment incentives. Subject to evaluation of the prototypes, a reformed dental contract could begin to be rolled out nationally from 2018/19 onwards.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-04-26T10:25:48.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513668/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513668/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513668/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-18","Dentistry: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether a timetable has been agreed for the review of the General Dental Practitioners contract.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","34416"
