parliament.uk/resources/513687/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-04-18","Probation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders in category (a) 1, (b) 2, and (c) 3 are being managed by multi-agency public protection arrangements (MAPPA) in England and Wales; and how many MAPPA-managed offenders there have been in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","34426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513688","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>In April 2014, the Government reformed crime outcome data to give greater transparency to the public about the investigation and prosecution of crime.</p><p>The requested outcomes data have been provided for the first available year (12 months to March 2015) and the most recent rolling year (12 months to September 2015) in the accompanying table. These have been given as proportions of recorded crimes recorded during the period rather than numbers as some forces were unable to supply data based on the new outcomes framework at the start of the period. The table also includes the proportion of crimes under active investigation awaiting an outcome from each period for further context.</p><p>More recent figures for the year to December 2015 will be published on Thursday April 21, 2016.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-04-21T11:56:54.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513688/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513688/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513688/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-18","Criminal Investigation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many investigations into crimes categorised as violent crimes and sexual offences were assigned an outcome of investigation complete - no suspect identified in (a) each year since 2010 and (b) the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","34427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513689","Home Office","false","2016-04-21","<p>All out of country entry clearance applications are subject to an extensive range of mandatory and discretionary checks. These include, but are not limited to, biographic and biometric identity checks against national and international police records and against previous immigration history, as well as document verification.</p><p>Applications are submitted at a Visa Application Centre (VAC) and are individually bundled. The bundles are sent to Decision Making Centres to be assessed by an Entry Clearance Officer, before being returned to the VAC. The application remains in individual bundles throughout the process to prevent applicants' details being confused with other cases.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-04-21T11:59:10.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513689/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513689/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513689/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-18","Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will put safeguards in place to ensure that (a) out of country entry clearance applications are rigorously checked, (b) all supporting documents for such applications are fairly considered and (c) applicants' details are not confused with other cases.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","34424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513690","Home Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>Complex Casework Directorate was set up to be responsible for the remaining un-concluded asylum cases where the initial asylum application was lodged before March 2007. The work to review and communicate decisions to the cohort of older asylum cases was completed by the end of December 2014, other than for a small number of cases that were on hold, although work continues to progress the removal of applicants who received a negative decision from the Home Office and who otherwise have no lawful basis to remain in the United Kingdom.</p><p>As of 31 December 2015 there were 524 older asylum records requiring review, and a further 742 were on hold. These cases were on hold for legitimate process reasons. There are no dormant records.</p><p>The older asylum records relate to asylum applications made prior to 5 March 2007, and there are therefore no new cases, although cases that are reopened following contact with an individual whose record was previously closed are added to the cohort of older live asylum records. It is not possible to say how many reopened cases were subsequently granted leave without incurring disproportionate cost.</p><p>Information relating to older asylum records is published as part of the Asylum Transparency Data. This data includes the work in progress, on take of people who enter the cohort and the number of individuals granted leave.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34450","2016-04-26T11:44:40.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513690/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513690/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513690/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-18","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many new cases have opened after the establishment of the Complex Casework Directorate; and how many such cases were resolved by way of granting a leave.","false","Biography information for Shabana Mahmood","Birmingham, Ladywood","Shabana Mahmood","34451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513691","Home Office","false","2016-04-26","<p>Complex Casework Directorate was set up to be responsible for the remaining un-concluded asylum cases where the initial asylum application was lodged before March 2007. The work to review and communicate decisions to the cohort of older asylum cases was completed by the end of December 2014, other than for a small number of cases that were on hold, although work continues to progress the removal of applicants who received a negative decision from the Home Office and who otherwise have no lawful basis to remain in the United Kingdom.</p><p>As of 31 December 2015 there were 524 older asylum records requiring review, and a further 742 were on hold. These cases were on hold for legitimate process reasons. There are no dormant records.</p><p>The older asylum records relate to asylum applications made prior to 5 March 2007, and there are therefore no new cases, although cases that are reopened following contact with an individual whose record was previously closed are added to the cohort of older live asylum records. It is not possible to say how many reopened cases were subsequently granted leave without incurring disproportionate cost.</p><p>Information relating to older asylum records is published as part of the Asylum Transparency Data. This data includes the work in progress, on take of people who enter the cohort and the number of individuals granted leave.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","34451","2016-04-26T11:44:40.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513691/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513691/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513691/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-04-18","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases are (a) awaiting a decision and (b) dormant at the Complex Casework Directorate in Liverpool