"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513195","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Research Councils do not employ any civil servants at any of their locations.</p><p>All people working in Research Councils are public servants and the numbers by location are shown on the attached table and represents the position as at 31 December 2015.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-20T14:32:52.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513195/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513195/answer","Attachment to 34240.xlsx","Attachment to 34240","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513195/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-15","Research Councils","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many civil servants were employed at each location by the Research Council in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513196","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-20","<p>The number of civil servants employed by the National Measurement and Regulation Office is shown in the attached table and represents the position as at 31 December 2015. The Department does not hold centrally any location data for its agencies prior to this date.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-20T14:38:07.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513196/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513196/answer","Attachment to 34241.xlsx","Attachment to 34241","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513196/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-15","National Measurement and Regulation Office","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many civil servants were employed at each location by the National Measurement and Regulation Office in the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513197","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p>Proposals to consider the Department’s BIS 2020 programme were received from McKinsey &amp; Company and The Boston Consulting Group.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-25T09:10:02.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513197/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513197/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-15","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which consultants other than McKinsey bid for the tender to consider his Department's BIS 2020 programme.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513198","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department has committed to reduce total operating spending by £350m a year by 2020, which is consistent with Spending Review 2015 outcomes. The BIS2020 programme aims to achieve the agreed savings by focusing on maximising efficiency so as to prioritise front line activity.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-04-25T09:13:07.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513198/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513198/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-15","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether it is planned that the BIS 2020 programme will make greater savings than the savings required under the Spending Review 2015 set by the Chancellor of the Exchequer.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","34232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513199","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2016-04-20T15:00:00.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513199/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513199/answer","UKSA response to PQ 34253.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Mean Annual Gross Pay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513199/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-15","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the mean annual gross pay was for jobs in (a) manufacturing, (b) services and (c) the whole economy in each of the last five years for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","34253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513200","Department for Education","false","2016-04-25","<p>We are taking a number of steps to ensure that the full range of education and training options are widely understood by young people. Schools are legally required to secure independent careers guidance for pupils up to the age of 18. This must include information on the full range of education and training options, including apprenticeships.</p><p>Destination measures are a key tool to assess how well schools and colleges prepare their students to make a successful transition into the next stage of education or training, or employment. The key stage 5 measure looks at activity in the year after the young person took A level or other level 3 qualifications. Destination measures will be one of the headline performance measures in the 2016 performance tables if the data are robust enough. They are taken into account by Ofsted during school inspections.</p><p>However, the range of information that young people receive remains too narrow and we want to ensure that young people hear much more consistently about the merits of alternatives to academic routes and are aware of all the routes to higher skills and into the workplace. The government intends to bring forward legislation at the earliest opportunity that will require schools to allow other education and training providers the opportunity to talk to students about their offer on school premises.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-04-25T16:34:15.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513200/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513200/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-15","Further Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that people leaving sixth form are fully aware of all further education options open to them.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","34237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513201","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-04-27","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Anti-dumping policy is agreed at EU level so all EU member states adopt identical trade measures to protect EU industry from dumping. These measures are only imposed following an investigation by the European Commission, which in turn must be prompted by a complaint from European industry. The EU currently has 37 anti-dumping and anti-subsidy measures in place on steel and steel products.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the International Comparisons Working Group, established following the Steel Summit on 16 October 2015, the Government has, in conjunction with representatives of the UK steel industry, examined the anti-dumping policies of some non-EU countries. The work was informed, in part, by European Commission’s own evaluation of its trade defence instruments published in 2012[1], which included a detailed comparison of the trade defence policies of other countries.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>[1] Evaluation of the European Union’s Trade Defence Instruments. BKP Development and Research 2012. Vol 1 and 2.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-04-27T15:26:06.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513201/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513201/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-04-15","Iron and Steel: Dumping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he has taken to examine measures other European countries have taken to protect their steel industries against dumping to inform his policies.","false","Biography information for Kevin Brennan","Cardiff West","Kevin Brennan","34225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513202","Cabinet Office","false","2016-04-20","<p>None.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-04-20T09:12:36.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513202/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513202/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-04-15","Cabinet Office: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513203","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-25","<p>No jobs in the Treasury or non-Departmental public bodies, executive agencies, advisory bodies falling under its remit have been abolished or relocated in the regions or time frames stated in the question.</p><p> </p><p>In April 2011, HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) – a non-ministerial Department falling under the remit of the Chancellor – closed Crewe House, an Enquiry Centre (EC), and relocated to Hornbeam House in Crewe. In 2014, following HMRC’s decision to close all ECs, the EC in Crewe was closed.</p><p> </p><p>In May 2011, Craven House, Macclesfield was closed and the EC relocated to Macclesfield Town Hall. In 2014, following HMRC’s decision to close all ECs, the EC in Macclesfield was closed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-25T16:07:27.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513203/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513203/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-15","Treasury: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513204","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-22","<p>The Government has committed to ensuring free software is available for those with the simplest affairs in order that businesses can meet the requirements of Making Tax Digital. In addition, many businesses are already using digital record-keeping tools to deal with their tax affairs.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has received a number of representations from individuals, businesses, professional bodies and the software industry about Making Tax Digital. Both I and officials from HM Treasury and HM Revenue and Customs have discussed the reforms with a wide range of professional bodies and advisory groups representing small businesses and the self-employed. Extensive consultation will take place throughout 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","33955","2016-04-22T10:17:07.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513204/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513204/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-15","Taxation: Self-assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what representations he has received from business groups (a) opposing and (b) supporting his plans to require small businesses to submit quarterly digital tax returns; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","34184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513205","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-20","<p>A number of Treasury officials were involved in preparing the Chancellor’s Budget Report. The government does not calculate the costs of producing individual charts at fiscal events.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-04-20T14:03:55.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513205/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513205/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-15","Budget March 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the (a) staff and (b) other costs to his Department were for the production of chart 1.5 on page 21 of the 2016 Budget Book.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513206","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Government has continued to improve the support and flexibility of parental pay and leave, spending around £3 billion a year on maternity payments to support pregnant women and new mothers and to help them achieve a better balance between their work and home lives.</p><p> </p><p>Self-employed mothers can receive Maternity Allowance. The standard rate of Maternity Allowance is the same as the standard rate of Statutory Maternity Pay.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-20T16:45:24.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513206/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513206/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-15","Maternity Pay: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to introduce maternity pay for self-employed women; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","34195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513207","HM Treasury","false","2016-04-20","<p>The abolition of Class 2 NICs means that 3.4 million self-employed individuals will gain by an average of £134 in 2018-19 when Class 2 National Insurance contributions are abolished. This will allow millions of self-employed individuals to keep more of their money and invest it back into growing their business, as well as ending an outdated and complex feature of the NICs system.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-04-20T16:44:11.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513207/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513207/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-04-15","National Insurance Contributions: Self-employed","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he has made an assessment as to how much the abolition of class 2 national insurance contributions will save on average for each self-employed person; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","34193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513208","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Department for Transport has estimated that on average it costs £53 to repair a pothole. However, the cost of filling an individual pothole will depend on a range of variables including geography, the type of road and whether the repair is temporary or permanent.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-20T15:29:24.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513208/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513208/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-15","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department has made an assessment of how much it costs on average to fill an individual pothole; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","34196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513209","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Northern Powerhouse is GREAT investment film, paid for by GREAT, was created to promote investment into all parts of the Northern Powerhouse. It has already been shown in Europe, North America, Latin America, Africa, Asia and Australasia. It was produced by Leeds agency Motiv Productions at a one off cost of just over £20,000.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-04-20T15:45:46.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513209/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513209/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-15","Economic Growth: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the cost to the public purse was of the promotional film for the Northern Powerhouse project, Gunning for growth.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","34214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513210","Department of Health","false","2016-04-21","<p>It is for providers to ensure that they are complying with legislation and paying workers for the time they are legally entitled to be paid for.</p><p> </p><p>The Care Act 2014 is clear that local authorities should ensure that care workers are paid at least minimum wage, and are paid for travel time between appointments.</p><p> </p><p>We are working with local authorities and the care sector to improve social care commissioning, including supporting the sector to commission in a way that promotes quality, including meeting legal requirements on staff pay in relation to travel time.</p><p> </p><p>There is clear Government Guidance on the issue of payment for work related travel time. It can be found in full on this website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/minimum-wage-different-types-work/overview" target="_blank">http://www.gov.uk/minimum-wage-different-types-work/overview</a></p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","34216","2016-04-21T13:59:52.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513210/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513210/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-04-15","Home Care Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department has issued to councils on the payment of homecare workers for their travel time.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","34217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513211","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-20","<p>Estimates on the number of kerbside collections of glass in the dry recycling stream are collated by the Waste and Resources Action Programme (WRAP). Data for 2014/15 shows that in England the number of authorities providing a kerbside collection for glass was 290 (89% of English authorities). This represented 19,768,943 (85%) of all households within England.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-04-20T16:28:31.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513211/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513211/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-15","Glass: Recycling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of councils in England that provide doorstep glass collection.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","34223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513212","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-20","<p>My Department is considering a number of issues related to the Building Regulations and the building control system. We will make an announcement about our plans in due course.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2016-04-20T13:11:45.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513212/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513212/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-15","Building Regulations: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, when his Department plans to review Building Regulations Approved Document B (Fire Safety).","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","34247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513213","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Department publishes statistics on local authority assistance to foreign nationals under homelessness provisions of the 1996 Housing Act. The latest statistics are available from table 785 of statutory homelessness statistics (see <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness</a>).</p><p>The Department does not require local authorities to submit data on the nationality of rough sleepers. However, we are considering the recommendations set out in the UK Statistics Authority report ‘Statistics on Homelessness and Rough Sleeping in England’ and are working on a development plan on how our statistics might best meet the need of users. On 12th April we held the first of a series of events with charities, local authorities and other users of our statistics. As part of those discussions the Department will consider what data we need to collect on rough sleepers.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-04-25T12:47:38.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513213/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513213/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-15","Homelessness: Nationality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 22 March 2016 to Question 31152, whether his Department plans to (a) record the nationalities of homeless people and rough sleepers and (b) use such nationality data to help tackle the root causes of homelessness.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","34173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513214","Department for Transport","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Pothole Action Fund is worth £250 million over the next five years to local highway authorities in England, outside London. On 7 April the Government announced the share each local highway authority will receive from the £50 million available for 2016/17. Funding is allocated according to the length of the road network each local highway authority is responsible for as set out in the Department for Transport Road Statistics Publication. Lancashire County Council received £1,241,000 from the Pothole Action Fund in 2016/17.</p><p> </p><p>Further details can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cash-for-councils-to-fill-almost-1-million-potholes" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/cash-for-councils-to-fill-almost-1-million-potholes</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-04-20T15:34:48.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513214/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513214/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-04-15","Roads: Lancashire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when Lancashire County Council made its application to the Pothole Action Fund; what level its application to that fund was awarded; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","34197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513215","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-04-25","<p>No jobs have been abolished or relocated since 2010, or will be abolished or relocated by 2020, in East Cheshire Local Authority in my Department or its Arms Length Bodies.</p>","Rayleigh and Wickford","Mr Mark Francois",,"2016-04-25T15:58:00.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513215/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Francois","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513215/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-04-15","Department for Communities and Local Government: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513216","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-25","<p>Core DCMS</p><p> </p><p>DCMS has not employed staff to work in East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and do not currently employ any staff in the area.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Other Bodies</p><p> </p><p>The abolition or relocation of jobs in the Department’s non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies is a matter for the Chief Executives of each of the bodies.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-25T08:26:52.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513216/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513216/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-15","Department for Culture, Media and Sport: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513217","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-04-20","<p>In the recently published Culture White Paper we made it clear that more needs to be done to encourage diversity in leadership positions. From this year, Arts Council England will publish data on leadership looking at the diversity profile of Chief Executives, Artistic Directors and Chairs of the organisations that they fund. In December 2015, the Arts Council announced four new strategic funds for diversity, totalling £8.6 million. This included £2.1 million for the Elevate fund which has been created to develop the strength, management and governance of diverse-led organisations outside the Arts Council's National Portfolio. A new £2.6 million Change Makers fund will fund long-term relationships between National Portfolio Organisations and aspiring arts leaders from the BME and deaf and disabled communities, providing valuable experience to individuals. Both of these funds are now open for applications.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-04-20T12:52:41.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513217/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513217/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-04-15","Arts: Leadership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress his Department has made in encouraging diversity in leadership positions in the culture sector.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","34172"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513218","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-04-21","<p>This information is not held in the format requested.</p><p>In April 2010 and January 2016 there were less than 10 Ministry of Defence (MOD) civilian personnel employed at locations within the Unitary Authority of Cheshire East.</p><p>Full details of how the planned reductions in MOD civilian staff numbers announced in the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 will be profiled over the next five years are not yet available and will be developed as programmes mature.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2016-04-21T15:37:25.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513218/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513218/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-04-15","Ministry of Defence: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many jobs in (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513219","Department for Education","false","2016-05-09","<p>Officials from across the Department were involved in different ways and at different times on work for the Education and Adoption Act. It is therefore not possible to distinguish costs from the wider business of the Department. There was no external legal or consultancy expenditure.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-05-09T14:08:59.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513219/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513219/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-15","Education and Adoption Act 2016","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department spent on (a) consultancy fees, (b) legal advice, (c) civil service staffing costs and (d) all other expenditure relating to the Education and Adoption Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513220","Department for Education","false","2016-04-22","<p>No jobs have been abolished or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-04-22T13:52:32.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513220/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513220/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-15","Department for Education: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of her Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513221","Department for Education","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Department does not specifically monitor exposure to electromagnetic fields in schools.</p><p> </p><p>We provide advice to schools on health and safety matters. Schools must take reasonable steps to ensure that staff and pupils are not exposed to risks to their health and safety by conducting a risk assessment and, if necessary, putting measures in place to minimise any known risk.</p><p> </p><p>Schools should be aware that where concerns are raised that they can access the appropriate advice; Public Health England provides advice via <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/electromagnetic-fields" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>[1] on exposure to electromagnetic fields in the everyday environment.</p><p>[1] https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/electromagnetic-fields</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","34233","2016-04-25T16:49:45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513221/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513221/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-15","Pupils: Electromagnetic Fields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department advises schools on the steps they should take to ensure that children are not over exposed to electromagnetic fields in schools.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","34234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513222","Department for Education","false","2016-04-25","<p>The Department does not specifically monitor exposure to electromagnetic fields in schools.</p><p> </p><p>We provide advice to schools on health and safety matters. Schools must take reasonable steps to ensure that staff and pupils are not exposed to risks to their health and safety by conducting a risk assessment and, if necessary, putting measures in place to minimise any known risk.</p><p> </p><p>Schools should be aware that where concerns are raised that they can access the appropriate advice; Public Health England provides advice via <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/electromagnetic-fields" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>[1] on exposure to electromagnetic fields in the everyday environment.</p><p>[1] https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/electromagnetic-fields</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","34234","2016-04-25T16:49:44.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513222/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513222/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-04-15","Pupils: Electromagnetic Fields","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether any monitoring by (a) her Department or (b) other bodies is carried out in schools to ensure that children are not overly exposed to electromagnetic fields.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","34233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513223","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-20","<p>Any nuclear reactor or facility proposed for deployment in the UK will be subject to robust and independent regulatory scrutiny.</p><p> </p><p>Therefore, any small modular reactor (SMR) design proposed for construction would undergo safety, security and environmental design assessment. A reactor design would only be allowed to progress if the independent regulator was satisfied it was compliant with the UK’s stringent safety standards.</p><p> </p><p>At Budget 2016, the Government committed to publishing a SMR delivery roadmap that will clarify the UK’s plan for addressing SMR related regulatory approvals, along with siting and skills issues.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-20T12:38:20.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513223/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513223/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-15","Nuclear Reactors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what assessment she has made of the likely timescale of type approval of first modular nuclear technology.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","34194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513224","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-25","<p>It is confirmed that no jobs in (a) the Department for Energy and Climate Change or (b) any of the Department’s accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 or (ii) will be abolished or relocated from the Authority by 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-25T15:38:03.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513224/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513224/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-15","Department for Energy and Climate Change: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of her Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513225","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-04-20","<p>The Government believes we will need to take the step of enshrining the global goal of net zero greenhouse gas emissions, reached at the UN climate summit at the end of 2015, into UK law. The question is not whether but how we do it. As a first step, our independent advisors, the Committee on Climate Change, is looking at the implications of the commitments in Paris, including the zero carbon emissions goal. It has said that it will report in the autumn. We will consider carefully the recommendations of the Committee.</p><p> </p><p>This Government is committed to the Climate Change Act and the target of at least an 80% reduction in greenhouse gas emissions by 2050. Our priority this year is setting the fifth carbon budget (covering the period 2028-32) by the end of June and developing our plan on how we will meet our existing targets. We are clear that this must be done while keeping our energy supply safe and costs as low as possible for hardworking families and businesses.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-04-20T12:38:05.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513225/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513225/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-04-15","Carbon Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals for the transition to a zero-carbon economy.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","34198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513226","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-25","<p>Protecting our pollinators is a priority for this Government. They are an essential part of our environment and play a crucial role in food production.</p><p> </p><p>Our National Pollinator Strategy sets out comprehensive measures to support pollinators and identifies actions for everyone, be they land managers, councils, or window-box gardeners, to do their bit.</p><p> </p><p>The “Bees’ Needs” campaign (www.beesneeds.org.uk) is included in the Strategy and explains what action can be taken to provide food, shelter and nest sites for pollinators. It contains a series of information sheets providing practical advice to local authorities, businesses and gardeners about managing urban or industrial green spaces and gardens for bees and other pollinators.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-04-25T17:00:37.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513226/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513226/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-15","Pollinators: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to incorporate a strategy on encouraging (a) public green spaces, (b) front gardens and (c) other private green spaces into the National Pollinator Strategy.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Pow","Taunton Deane","Rebecca Pow","34182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513227","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-25","<p>We have the highest standards of animal welfare in the world and no changes were ever planned to the animal welfare legislation upholding them, or to the strict enforcement and penalties that apply.</p><p> </p><p>Defra sought views from interested parties in 2013 to inform the consultation on the principle of reforming the farm animal welfare codes, not regulation. Those that responded included animal welfare charities, the livestock industry, enforcement agencies, expert committees, academics, veterinarians, and members of the public. A list of respondents is included in the Government response published in 2015: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/farm-animal-welfare-codes-reform" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/farm-animal-welfare-codes-reform</a></p><p> </p><p>In the light of views raised, the Government has given the matter further consideration and believes that its animal welfare objectives can be achieved by retaining statutory codes. The Government will continue to work with industry to ensure farmers have the guidance they need to help them comply with legislation and we will consult with interested parties as and when updates are needed.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","34178 ; 34179 ; 34181","2016-04-25T16:56:05.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513227/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513227/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-15","Poultry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what changes she plans to make to her Department's code on chicken farming.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","34180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513228","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-25","<p>We have the highest standards of animal welfare in the world and no changes were ever planned to the animal welfare legislation upholding them, or to the strict enforcement and penalties that apply.</p><p> </p><p>Defra sought views from interested parties in 2013 to inform the consultation on the principle of reforming the farm animal welfare codes, not regulation. Those that responded included animal welfare charities, the livestock industry, enforcement agencies, expert committees, academics, veterinarians, and members of the public. A list of respondents is included in the Government response published in 2015: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/farm-animal-welfare-codes-reform" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/farm-animal-welfare-codes-reform</a></p><p> </p><p>In the light of views raised, the Government has given the matter further consideration and believes that its animal welfare objectives can be achieved by retaining statutory codes. The Government will continue to work with industry to ensure farmers have the guidance they need to help them comply with legislation and we will consult with interested parties as and when updates are needed.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","34179 ; 34180 ; 34181","2016-04-25T16:56:05.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513228/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513228/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-15","Livestock: Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the potential effect on animal welfare of self-regulation of the livestock farming and breeding industries.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","34178"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513229","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-25","<p>Not all of the Defra Group (Core and her non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies) collect data on posts that have been abolished or relocated; although all collect management information about the people working in the East Cheshire Local Authority area.</p><p> </p><ol><li><p>In the Department we do not hold data on posts that have been abolished or relocated in the East Cheshire Local Authority area between March 2010 and now. There are currently no plans to abolish jobs in or relocate any jobs from the East Cheshire Local Authority area by 2020.</p><p> </p></li><li><p>Not all of the Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies hold data on posts that have been abolished or relocated in the East Cheshire Local Authority area. Of those that do hold this data, during the period March 2010 to now 20 posts have been abolished. There are also currently no plans to abolish jobs in the East Cheshire Local Authority area by 2020.</p></li></ol>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-04-25T17:01:10.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513229/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513229/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-15","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Cheshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many jobs in (a) her Department and (b) each of her Department's non-departmental public bodies, executive agencies, non-ministerial departments, advisory bodies and other accountable statutory bodies (i) have been abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority since 2010 and (ii) will be abolished in or relocated from East Cheshire Local Authority by 2020.","false","Biography information for Tristram Hunt","Stoke-on-Trent Central","Tristram Hunt","34156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513230","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-04-25","<p>We have the highest standards of animal welfare in the world and no changes were ever planned to the animal welfare legislation upholding them, or to the strict enforcement and penalties that apply.</p><p> </p><p>Defra sought views from interested parties in 2013 to inform the consultation on the principle of reforming the farm animal welfare codes, not regulation. Those that responded included animal welfare charities, the livestock industry, enforcement agencies, expert committees, academics, veterinarians, and members of the public. A list of respondents is included in the Government response published in 2015: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/farm-animal-welfare-codes-reform" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/farm-animal-welfare-codes-reform</a></p><p> </p><p>In the light of views raised, the Government has given the matter further consideration and believes that its animal welfare objectives can be achieved by retaining statutory codes. The Government will continue to work with industry to ensure farmers have the guidance they need to help them comply with legislation and we will consult with interested parties as and when updates are needed.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","34178 ; 34179 ; 34180","2016-04-25T16:56:05.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513230/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/513230/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-04-15","Animal Welfare","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what changes she plans to make to her Department's official guidance on animal welfare standards.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Hudd